caption_text: Pacifiction (2022) ➡️ 9/10 Writing about this indescribable movie makes little sense. Albert Serra’s(or as he refers to himself: the greatest Spanish director alive) last movie Liberté revolved around the beautiful topic of sodomy practiced by a bunch of libertines expelled from Louis XVI's court, so I was ready to see heavy stuff similar to old men in wigs pissing in each other’s mouth but that’s not what Serra delivered. Because he’s that kind of unique director who can’t and won’t repeat himself (not like so many famous ones repeating the only formula with the only cast that ever worked for them, never leaving their or the audience’s comfort zone) and who can build an atmosphere no other can. This is an example of the highest level of cinematic art, a truly challenging task for a moviegoer. So it didn’t win in Cannes but who the fuck cares. I'm so grateful for talents who make it possible for us to see stuff we only see in our dreams while we’re awake. French Polynesia this, colonization that, the really subtle plot here isn’t what really matters. Being sucked into this fever dream while not being annoyed by the languorous takes, the repressed dialogues or the lack of tangible happenings is what does. 3 things that went through my mind. 1. I wish I could do something that can argue with the Godard quote: Nothing is original. 2. When my eyes aren’t indulged by orange and pink mergers on various beautiful textures of nature, the movie delivers a pile of scenes I can only compare to the way of seeing your surroundings after coming out of the sea, laying on a sunbed, opening your eyes, and let the drops of water from the end of your eyelashes fall into your eyes while looking straight into the sun. Doesn’t make sense, right? Watch the movie and it will. 3. It’s almost over and the only inspirations that came to my mind were Wim Wenders, his colors and his eccentric characters, and god yes Claire Denis but just because of the blue club scene with the admiral that gave me the same chills as the end scene of Denis’ Beau Travail. Be open, let the incredibly composed scenes, out of this world colors and Benoît Magimel’s genius performance run through you. #onemovieaday

The Apartment (1960) ➡️ 7,5/10 
Billy Wilder’s second collaboration with Jack Lemmon which apparently helped making a key transition in his career turning from a light comedian to a tragic everyman. While it overall feels like a nice romantic comedy it has so much melancholy and sadness in its centerpoint laying low and screaming loud at the same time through dialogues, widescreen b&w compositions, and basically the topic of faceless capitalism’s goodhearted slaves to the company’s or the desired powerful man’s value system. Those, who have to be reminded that they have other things in life than their jobs and being used and manipulated by powerful people, executives and bosses to make a romantic leap, and put the paycheck lower on their priority list, even if they are weighted down with the trials and responsibilities of working for a living. Men and women are being trapped in different ways in the same trap and infinite loop of people-pleasing tactics to get along in life and to climb up the ladder, the succes of which is decided by people without any empathy or humanity. The vibe of the whole movie is not as serious as it might have sounded in the aforementioned, it is easy to watch, it looks really flattering, its cinematography tells a lot of stories helping to understand the dynamics, the distance building environment and period of time, it doesn’t end in tragedy but it has the underlining sadness all over it. And Jack Lemmon in sunglasses and that coat just looks amazing.

Close (2022) ➡️ 7/10
Belgian director Lukas Dhont's second film after his debut, Girl (2018). It won the Grand Prix in Cannes alongside Claire Denis’s Stars at Noon. This fact raised my thoughts about how different these two winners are. Denis’s cinema is never easy to watch, it asks a lot from the audience, the form is rather unorthodox, requires attention, a certain mood and persistence. It really works or it really doesn’t, and it usually depends on the state of the recipient. And I admire that. Taking the risk of not compromising. Close is a really different kind of filmmaking in my book. I couldn’t stop noticing film school storytelling techniques, the film language was kindergarden level for me. I’m tired of the usual, cliché tools of showing that if a character struggles mentally, he can’t perform well in sports. How he always runs from left to right when he is with his friend, but from right to left with other kids after he loses him (so many running scenes, the DoP really made sure it was worth renting the camera tracking vehicle). I understand its importance, I value its emotional education, I think it should be a curriculum in elementary school, but because I consider myself a sensitive and high EQ person, I don’t feel like it taught me anything new, therefore I was bored even though it’s about something very sad and tragic. It examines the fateful and destructive consequences when the infinitely pure, innocent and instinctive unconditional love between two people (children in this case) is suddenly exposed to external forces outside the relationship. How fragile something elementally strong can suddenly become as soon as we put the opinions of the uncomprehending crowd ahead of our own and our loved one’s feelings. I liked the topic of the movie. I like a story about not conventional love of any kind when the factor of the ‘between whom it happens’ or ‘what is the nature of it’ doesn't matter. It’s a good education. But it made me think of Xavier Dolan’s captivating movies, especially Matthias & Maxime, which has some similarities with Close, although it portrays the same inside struggles in adult men. Better.

Zero Fucks Given (2021) ➡️ 7/10
Watching Adèle Exarchopoulos slowly burst into tears in the middle of a long scene is a very special experience. Luckily we can have this experience again. I fell in love with her in the production-wise infamous ‘Blue Is the Warmest Color’. This talented woman and her radiating sincerity is a guarantee of slashing realism. In that movie the name of her character was changed to Adèle because the director (Abdellatif Kechiche) - who enforced method acting throughout the production - recorded and used a lot of scenes about her, when she wasn’t acting. When she was eating on set, or sleeping on the train going to the next set. In these scenes everyone called her by her real name, so they decided to name the character the same. In the breakup scene Adéle was not only crying because of acting but also due incredible fatigue caused by the director making them do hundreds of takes for small scenes to achieve the desired realism of the story, without breaks. Back to today’s movie, Exarchopoulos’ performance in Zero Fucks Given is more documentary than slick. It shows perfectly the soul crushing monotony and alienating nature of the flight attendant profession on a low-cost airline. That first half of the movie is fantastic, including the scene, when her telco company calls her to upgrade her plan, but the contract is on her mom’s name and we see her face during the call when she explains why it would be very difficult for her dead mom to change her plan. That’s when we get those kind of tears she as a person and not just an actress can’t possibly hold back. It’s her specialty and she doesn’t even know it. It becomes obvious that this movie is about a way of grieving, a way of fleeing from reality. As the misogynist and slaveristic (I know it’s not a word) characteristics of this profession get through to the viewer, her life changes and we get a deeper look at her family, the other members of the joint grief and how they cope with it. That part was way too long for me. 30 min could have been easily edited out. But all in all a remarkable debut feature from writer-directors Emmanuel Marre and Julie Lecoustre.

EO (2022) ➡️ 5,5/10
Veteran director Jerzy Skolimowski (84) made this feature paying homage to Robert Bresson’s 1966 donkey tale ‘Au Hasard Balthazar’ probably because as he said that was the only movie ever made him cry. EO surprisingly won the Jury Prize in Cannes and as much as it was supposed to be somehow the year of donkeys in cinema (The Banshees of Inisherin, Triangle of Sadness) in EO the donkey (all of them since there were multiple donkeys playing the protagonist) is not a ancillary, or just a metaphor as in the mentioned movies, but totally in focus, since we watch the journey of one throughout Europe after getting released from a circus, encountering human crualty and human kindness. I think I’m a horrible person because I already felt incredibly uncomfortable when the first close up of a tear in a donkey’s eye rolled down on its face. It didn’t manage to put me under its spell. I get the homage, I get that the director loves animals, but first of all he said it’s a “little bit of a protest against the indignitirs suffered by animals”, well things that are a little bit of something are not really for me. Especially if they are full of corny cliches. The landscape shots really felt like watching a Terrence Malick movie but instead of Christan Bale or Fassbender I was looking at a donkey, and the scenes of caricaturistic post-socialist country vibes felt like watching a Radu Jude movie but were ruined by the - I am really sorry to say this, but - boomer directing. How an average 84 yo imagines journalists or a metal fan today… There were great parts and characters (I was zoning out hard, when Isabelle Huppert appeared on the screen as a surprise) and remarkable DoP work and I’m glad that the director and his wife are vegetarians now, but other than that I don’t think it’s an amazing movie in 2022. So it probably means it has a massive chance to win an Oscar.

Two Lovers (2008) ➡️ 7,5/10 
I posted about James Gray’s latest movie, Armageddon Time, not long ago. Somehow I didn't know about the existence of this movie he made 14 years before, with Joaquin Phoenix and Gwyneth Paltrow. A footage from it just happened to come across while scrolling. Phoenix is pretty much always a guarantee that you are not going to waste your time watching something he is in, this example strengthens the rule. He is just incredible as always in this complex portrait of human or inhuman relationships often mistaken as love. The Jewish family of his character, Leonard lives in Brighton Beach, Brooklyn which comes across so gritty and melancholic that you have to let your eyes get used to the darkness of the screen in the beginning. Leonard is a depressed, probably bipolar man torn between two different women. The exciting, vivacious and impulsive, egocentric Michelle and the silent, understanding, helpful, therefore obviously not as exciting, also Jewish Sandra. The latter is probably called Plan B in his head. The movie portrays the rare case when your parents are actually right about how “you should marry the nice woman.” The girl next door. Funny, that in this movie the woman who actually lives next door is Michelle, keeping Leonard in constant anxiety and a state of hopeless craving. But what we understand during the film is that Leonard and his so special and at first sight just simply weird (unique) being is much more torn apart by his past and the injustice of love and fate. The film is not just a love triangle story but a nuanced exploration of family dynamics, mental illness, and the complexity of human emotions and toxic love. Newman's score adds emotional weight to the story and amplifies the feelings of sadness, longing, and heartbreak. Its melancholia reminded me of Blue Valentine (2010) because of its poignant and realistic portrait of a failing relationship.

Sharper (2023) ➡️ 6,5/10 
Semi-entertaining A24 Sunday movie with a lot of twists, a jigsaw puzzle page-turner structure, mediocre acting (except Julianne Moore who is great and Justice Smith who is horrible as always). Each part makes you want to watch the next inspired by the good old Rashomon-style storyline where the same event is recounted by several characters while also moving the story a little bit forward revealing a little bit more. Obviously it is far from Park Chan-wook’s The Handmaiden, which adapted the Rashomon style masterfully but it is alright. Have to admit the montage part of the well-known “a character is being trained by a master running, reading, answering to questions and playing chess to intense and uplifting music” is really ridiculous when someone is training to be a con-artist and not a professional boxer. It made me laugh and it didn’t intend to do that.

Infinity Pool (2023) ➡️ 7,5/10
If you hold a gun to my head to tell you what Brandon Cronenberg’s new movie with Mia Goth (god bless this talented creature for real) and Alexander Skarsgård is like I will say it’s like a dream I’d have after a one day long movie marathon watching the best films of Lanthimos, Cronenberg senior, Pasolini, Bunuel, Jordan Peele, Nicolas Winding Refn, and the first season of White Lotus, shot in Hungary. And I am not exaggerating. First of all my dreams are exactly like this, luckily or not, I haven't decided yet. And second of all, all the mentioned influences appear crystal clearly in this opus shot in Hungary and Croatia. The credit’s graphic design by itself is really satisfying for the eye, but seeing all those familiar names in it (congrats my friend @endresomos - one of the location scouts for finding these places that help to put this story into a nonexistent 3rd world context - where else than Hungary lol) feels really good. Besides this praising I have to mention that Infinity Pool wants to be a social commentary on the hedonistic bourgeoisie so much that it almost shits itself, but if you forgive this and just let it (or Mia Goth’s again amazing performance - this woman’s going to make me converted to bisexuality i swear) entertain you, you can have a good time.

War Pony (2022) ➡️ 8/10 
Once upon a time there was Andrea Arnold who made the film ‘American Honey’ capturing that propulsive teenage trait of not being able to sit still, constantly fleeing from hopelessness, always on the move with other outcasts in the middle of the USA. Apart from Shia LaBeouf and Elvis's granddaughter Riley Keough (Zola, The Florida Project) the cast was mostly made up of nonactors. One day Riley had a scene together with two Native American extras Franklin Sioux Bob and Bill Reddy. They hung out all day talking on set, the guys shared their stories with her growing up on the Pine Ridge Reservation designated as one of the poorest areas in the United States. Later Riley went home and told her roommate, long time best friend and co-creator Gina Gammel (another white privileged woman from Australia) about them. They visited Pine Ridge quite often filming things together with the boys, hanging out, being creative. Several years later Gammel and Keough’s truly collaborative directorial debut ‘War Pony’ written by Franklin and Bill premiered at the Cannes Film Festival and won the Camera d’Or, the prize for best first film. The story of making this movie sums up the essence of creating, how curiosity, intentions and the will to raise awareness while being white women are sometimes not enough by itself, when you consider how many obstacles the directors had to overcome during making it. They were told by potential producers that their story wasn’t relatable or sad enough, or even that it needed a white protagonist. Luckily they finished it in a way they wanted to so the end product isn’t a (usual on subjects like this) sufferporn but it remains sensitive and it’s not afraid of using humor, even if it’s bittersweet. All in all it feels that it’s not a movie made by complete outsider white people pretending to care so they can win awards (Hi whole advertising industry winning in Cannes with scams) but by some people who let their curiosity drive them and take the effort to spend time and energy on getting to know how they can portray something authentically. Thank you @cinema_niche for the opportunity to see it on the big screen. #onemovieaday

Flux Gourmet (2022) ➡️ 7,5/10
I don’t think I should really like this movie, but surprisingly I do. As much as I am not a fan of anything that’s put in the genres of horror and comedy at the same time, and I also haven’t even seen the previous movies (eg. In Fabric - A24) from the writer director Peter Strickland, somehow I really enjoyed this bizarre tale of a culinary sonic performance collective. It was such an offbeat approach that it made me curious. During the workshop, the performances of the collective in this Sonic Catering Institute is being documented by Stones, the journalist, who meanwhile suffers through the worst kind of gastroenterological nightmares himself. Even tho most of the characters are cartoon-like caricatures, especially the owner and director of the institute Gwendoline Christie (Severance, Game of Thrones, Star Wars) and the male member of the collective played by the for me insufferable Asa Butterfield (Sex Education) the whole movie builds up in a way that you find comfort and sense in it. It evokes sincere emotions, it makes great comments about integrity and commercialism, and the fragility of artistic collaborations. And meanwhile it plays out well how the documenting journalist goes from observation to full-on participation in the performances by his examinations revolving around his bloated stomach pain and wish for solitude or noise so he can fart. A lot of scenes revoked the absurdism and conceptual surrealism of Bunuel for me and I would say I liked this movie for all the reasons I didn’t like The Menu (I didn’t even post about it, that's how much I look down on that film) if we stick to culinary topics. Actual People (2021) ➡️ 5/10
Writer, director Kit Zauhar stars in her feature debut which feels like an alright student thesis film and didn’t do much more to me than making me think: God, I hope this is not how actual 22 years old people are in New York. But I’m afraid it was meant to portray reality in the interpretation of asian-american Kit Zauher who plays a NY uni student from Philly during her last week of school dealing with the unspeakable fear of going out to the so-called real world, where actual people actually have to work, have to learn how not to be annoyingly whiny, or have to be able to not make horrible (if any) decisions even if they are single. She’s not really good at any of these things so I get her angst. This movie obviously was inspired by and aspired to something like Lena Dunham’s ‘Tiny Furniture’ (2010) or Greta Gerwig’s ‘Frances Ha’ (2012). I was not a fan of either, so I was obviously not impressed by this low-budget version of mumblecore naturalist heaven. I think I would have punched myself in the face if I had been like this at 22, but that’s okay I have different kinds of existential crisis problems, probably more Central European ones. Watching a movie like this always reminds me of the genre-creating mumblecore classic of Noah Baumbach ‘Kicking and Screaming’ (2005), his first movie, but as boomer as it sounds that was made in such a different time I guess that view on graduation anxiety is not relevant anymore.

Causeway (2022) ➡️ 7/10

I finally got around to watching this film, which I had been putting off for months because of my dislike of Jennifer Lawrence. But since I'm also procrastinating watching the last episode of Atlanta simply because I don't want it to end, I wanted to see Brian Tyree Henry in something else, especially now that he's been nominated for an Oscar for his performance in the film. It would have been a 5/10 for me if he wasn't in it, but this way it's a solid 7. Thank goodness it's only 92 minutes long, so they managed to keep it compact, not stretching out the misery for an eternity. I don't know much about the director, but she directed some (?) episodes of Room 104, one of my favourite Duplass Brothers projects. Causeway is a decent film, it's nothing spectacular, it's about two people who are broken for different reasons finding comfort in each other’s company while fighting their own not willing to leave demons by simply fleeing from them or neglecting them. And it almost manages to leave out the love thread completely (Maniac is still my first choice when it comes to a story with a man and a woman protagonist not having a love affair at all). Its quality perfectly blends the A24 vibes with the sterility of an Apple TV production. It's nothing special, but it's worth a watch in case you don’t have anything more anticipated to check. I was wondering how come the woke police didn’t have a problem with Lawrence playing a lesbian woman tho.

Babylon (2022) ➡️ 5/10 
Yeah I’m guilty, I had a lazy Sunday and an almost empty giant cinema hall on my hands so I caved in and watched Damien Chazelle’s latest ridiculously expensive 3 hours long (feels like 4 tbh) money shots. Although one can’t argue with the fact that on a lazy Sunday these things are sometimes perfect matches for your empty mind. In case you’re not planning to fill it with any ideas or thoughts. Apart from the fact that you can feel the money burning with every second of this confused, plot- and pointless cavalcade (if anything that’s why the name if accurate) you can also realize how this movie is the reason why the most generic imdb synopsis was born: “A tale of outsized ambition and outrageous excess, it traces the rise and fall of multiple characters during an era of unbridled decadence and depravity in early Hollywood”. Bruh. 😀 Imagine a director having this as a pitch. I am all on board with The Guardian's review in this case, I would not waste any more words on it. Let me just highlight my favourite part of the movie (the end), when in an entire - supposedly cathartic - block Chazalle hits you with scenes from the most powerful, progressive and legendary early films FROM EUROPE, which have nothing to do with the previous 3 hours “tale” of early Hollywood. Putting Bunuel scenes or shots from Louis Feuillade’s silent crime serial film ’Les Vampires’ inbetween 4k slow motion shots of paint drops dissolving in water. I mean yeah, if anything this was and is Hollywood most of the time. Thank you for summarising it for us.

Sick of Myself (2022) ➡️ 7,5/10

I rarely read about movies I know I will watch as soon as they get released. So I didn’t read anything about Kristoffer Borgli’s cruel black comedy, his first feature film either. ‘Sick of myself’ is kind of the sadist ‘The Worst Person in the World’, and not only because it’s also norwegian and Anders Danielsen Lee is also in it (for one minute), but because it is literally about someone (or someones) who could easily be called the worst. This satire really pushes the limits of how it is “okay” or “allowed” to talk about personality disorders or mental illnesses, and meanwhile looks so incredibly good that you almost forget to feel bad. Cronengberg’s body horror and prothetics department can pull up its sock compared to this and it’s not even trying hard. Also big up for the costume department, I want all the clothes but especially the “Father figure” shirt in my wardrobe. And to get back to where I started, I didn’t know anything about this film but at the end I felt like what I saw was shot in a way (the slow zooms), color graded in a way and had the vibe and humour just like a Vimeo Staff Pick short film I saw 2 years ago. The Triangle of Sadness (2022) ➡️ 8,5/10
I remember watching Ruben Östlund’s Force Majeure in the cinema in 2014. After 20 minutes almost everyone left the room not because of any Trier or Gaspar Noe “cool sexy disgusting reasons”, but because the Hungarian title of the movie was Lavina, and almost noone expected a psychological drama instead of a disaster movie. Since then Östlund’s work changed a bit, he won the Palme d’Or with The Square in 2017 and now again with the Triangle of Sadness. And although this one is a bit more didactic it is one of his most entertaining movies. I loved The Square too but it was a bit exhausting after a point. The Triangle of sadness also pulls you through a lot and at the third act it might feel a little long but luckily it stays entertaining, disgusting, explicit and engaging. Woody Harrelson as a burntout communist, and Harris Dickinson as one of the best looking guy I have ever seen (watch the movie ‘Beach Rats’ with him playing the main character if you have a chance, I think it’s even available on Netflix now) by themselves are enough to watch this black comedy about gender roles, fake-feminism, and class struggle. Certainly scratch the itch for those who love Bunuel (me) as it definitely evokes The Discreet Charm of the Burgeoisie and The Exterminating Angel. And please watch it in the cinema because Östlund played really well with the Roy Andersson kindalike compositions and a lot of little sound games that make you love cinema. Last but not least my favourite Fred Again-The Blessed Madonna track is playing during the last scene and the credits so it really puts you in a good mood when you go home. 
P.S. If you have a Mubi subscription, check out Östlund’s short movie Incident by a Bank from 2009. Thank you, good night.

Some Kind of Heaven (2020) ➡️ 8,5/10
I got so engaged at the very first moment of this documentary directed by Lance Oppenheim, produced by Darren Aronofsky and also (fun fact) Jeffrey Soros, nephew of George Soros. I can get really excited when a documentary doesn't look like shit just because it's a documentary. It's beautifully photographed and really entertaining. The topic is as surreal as it sounds: the biggest retirement community in Florida called "The Villages" with 130 000 "citizens" living the time of (the dawn of) their lives. I've been once to Florida and I enjoy the whole aesthetics and visual culture attached to it so i'm always pleased to watch movies that were shot there and can capture that atmosphere. Oppenheim didn't make a movie about the whole history of this weird community, although we get to know that this Disney Land for pensioners - or how some of them call it: "God's waiting room for heaven" - was created for Baby Boomers in the concept of making them feel nostalgia and peace in a bubble far from every inconveniences. Meaning: The Villages has its own Newspaper and TV News where the most important piece of news is that a citizen bought a new red roadster after years of driving a family car. The town was designed in a way to make them feel home -  meaning where they were born. Oppenheim takes us to a journey with 4 different individuals living there, searching for solace and emotional security. A married couple, a widow, and a kinda fuckboy (let's call him fuckgentleman since he is like 80) living in a van searching for a nice bimbo preferably with money and a house in The Villages. I didn't really think this topic can have such an effect on me as it did, but one can never know. I had a great time and my eyes were also entertained throughout the movie. Watch it.

Playtime (1967)➡️ 8/10
Jacques Tati's movie is exceptional from so many aspects. It resonates with writings of the Situationist International movement's avant-garde authors and intellectuals. It shows the dark side of monotony and automatisation caused by capitalism, and the alienating impact of technology. It merges comedy gags with social commentary. It reacts to the political effects on urbanisation during the de Gaulle regime and it predicted (in a symbolic way) the happenings of '68 May in Paris, the student riots. It makes fun of American tourists' approach of the city, but doesnt stop at showing the automatised labyrinth, it also shows a way out of the New Babylon with so clever metaphors. Creating a new harmony, in which people can fulfill their creative potential. It all starts at the Royal Garden, the turning point begins there and after a while we can also hear some guests singing "a la Bastille on aime bien.." in a restaurant named ROYAL garden. :D It encourages the spectators to become actively involved in the happenings, avoids close-ups, so not even Monsieur Hulo (played by Tati himself) becomes a protagonist. It's everyone, or noone. Tati used background noises conceptually, intensifying them rather into foreground noises all along, which brings a great tension throughout the movie. "The film is not about the place we live but about the way we use it."
